<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-08-14T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-08-14T13:00:00-05:00" n="419" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d419">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 659.110/430</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Page</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-08-14T19:00:00+01:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">August 14, 1918, 7 p.m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received August 15, 2
                                    a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>1104. War Trade Board [from <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SLP1">Sheldon</persName>]:</p>
                            <p>No. 1234. State Department No. 716, August 10, 4 p.m. Have consulted
                                British authorities who call attention to the fact that the telegram
                                deals only with tonnage and so far as it goes it seems quite
                                satisfactory to them. They regard as of extreme importance the other
                                part of the agreement which relates to the limitation of exports to
                                Germany. They have not heard from Washington the result of the
                                discussion with regard to the latter and must await further advice
                                [before] giving full concurrence.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Page</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>